    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "With the 'network value' I mean this indication:\r\n\r\n<img width=\"834\" alt=\"64119803-57540c00-cda3-11e9-948a-cbf81bcf8082\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8749671/67403863-38137700-f5bb-11e9-9f4d-2672abb1d289.png\">\r\n\r\nYes, we have ETHri/ETHro indicating that it's something non-mainnet and USD values on TestNet are 0 everywhere disregard ETH/token amounts. \r\n<img width=\"361\" alt=\"Screenshot 2019-10-23 at 18 28 55\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8749671/67409773-b07e3600-f5c3-11e9-8f86-66dc97731b8d.png\">\r\n\r\nBut, in my opinion, it doesn't solve the part of \"Send ETH on mainnet thinking it's testnet\" (because we'll have all \"indications\" on TestNet only - 0/no_USD value or ETHro/ETHri or `TestNet` network) which user may not even know and get used to it by using Status. \r\nFrom another point, having many indications on TestNet only (ETHro + No/Zero USD value + TestNet label) increase the strength of awareness when user is on Mainnet... And considering we default for all new/recovered accounts to Mainnet we at the same time consider users are using actively Mainnet so they should notice the difference between Mainnet or Testnet...\r\n\r\nOk, both cases works for me :) \r\n1) Having only 'testnet' indications (0 USD everywhere and ETHro/ERTHri as asset - we have already) + in scope of that issue we'll get a Network: Ropsten/Rinkeby/Goerli (by the way, would it make sense then to have 'Testnet' suffix here, so `Network:`................ `(?) Ropsten (Testnet)` ?\r\n2) We display network in `Sending...` bottom sheet view whether it's Mainnet or Testnet.\r\n\r\nI think the first item above has most votes then.  \r\n\r\n\r\n",
